          <fr:day>8</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/preface-0001/</fr:uri>
        <fr:display-uri>preface-0001</fr:display-uri>
        <fr:route>/preface-0001/</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Naive handling of material followed by rigorous presentation">Naive handling of material followed by rigorous presentation</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <html:p>There is a "naive" introduction to some of the material: in <fr:link href="/ela/" title="Elementary linear algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela/" display-uri="ela" type="local">Elementary linear algebra</fr:link>, for example, we just assume the real numbers exist and familiarity with calculating with them (at least to the level expected of a calculus student). But it isn't until <fr:link href="/ca/" title="Classical Analysis" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca/" display-uri="ca" type="local">Classical Analysis</fr:link> where <html:em>constructing</html:em> real numbers is really examined.</html:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors>
          <fr:author>
            <fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link>
          </fr:author>
        </fr:authors>
        <fr:date>
          <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
          <fr:month>12</fr:month>
          <fr:day>8</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/preface-0002/</fr:uri>
        <fr:display-uri>preface-0002</fr:display-uri>
        <fr:route>/preface-0002/</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Circular learning of Mathematics">Circular learning of Mathematics</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <html:p>Arguably this "circular" treatment of material is a pedagogical virtue when actually "executed" in practice: the student will study <fr:link href="/ela/" title="Elementary linear algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela/" display-uri="ela" type="local">Elementary linear algebra</fr:link> one quarter, then intermediate linear algebra the next quarter, then <fr:link href="/ca/" title="Classical Analysis" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca/" display-uri="ca" type="local">Classical Analysis</fr:link> the following quarter. This spaces out the material and the review, which strengthens mental connections.</html:p>
        <html:p>For better or worse, this forest of notes lacks that quality. After all, you can sit down and just "cram" the notes, possibly over the course of several days. So for you, the reader, you will not have the advantage of spaced learning.</html:p>
        <html:p>Also I am being a bit sparse when giving proofs in the earlier parts of the forest. So <fr:link href="/ela/" title="Elementary linear algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela/" display-uri="ela" type="local">Elementary linear algebra</fr:link> lacks proofs for every theorem, but they could be supplied if desired.</html:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
